    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Consumer Buying Behaviour in  Krishna Sai Granites (India) Pvt.Ltd</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Sindhu P.R</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Consumer Buying Behaviour<br />Krishna Sai Granites (India) Pvt.Ltd</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">May-2011 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">P5359</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">The stone industry is probably the oldest industry around, and the competition has been thickening ever since. We are facing and will continue to face competition from numerous forces, both direct and indirect. Ever since the Indian stone industry’s boom in early 1990’s we have seen so many players trying to grab a share of the pie but only a few have come out successful. Some lost out because of poor management while others succumbed to poor marketing. The fundamental of marketing is, “you can only sell a viable product”. Someone has rightly said, “A good product will sell itself.” However, only good raw materials and quality processing can only bring out good product.
Importantly, dealing with the right customers. It is extremely crucial to find customers with a long-term vision of maintaining and developing a rewarding relationship for all parties involved. It is also your responsibility to ensure an enduring relationship by consistently providing great products and services.
The customer should have a good reason for buying from you. As a manufacturer, you have to look for various means to gain a competitive edge in the market, giving your customer an advantage in his market. And good reasons do not necessarily include the lowest prices, but reasonable and competitive prices.
As an industry, with support from the government, we should make dedicated efforts to promote Indian stones abroad, the way Singapore and Malaysia promote themselves across the world to increase interest and awareness in the minds of the final consumers. Trade shows like these should also be marketed aggressively to increase the enthusiasm in Indian stone across the globe. These efforts will also counteract against threats to our natural advantage from artificial stones like Breton stone, which are quickly gaining popularity. Let us all involved with the industry promote the worth of natural stone and increase its value for the final consumer. All the promotion bodies should also actively involve themselves in promoting Indian stone.Secondly, we should actively look to discover and introduce new colors in the market. The government should also directly involve in helping to do so with the help of the technology at their disposal and also helping in terms of the legalities involved. Let us also look to utilize the information available about various deposits of natural stone gathered by government agencies like the Geological Survey of India.
Thirdly, we should, as a group, produce and supply high quality products at all times. We have to stress on timely deliveries too. Failing to deliver, both on time and quality will seriously affect the credibility of Indian stone industry. We have the potential to match and successfully compete against the sprawling stone industries across the world. A bottleneck to this is the under-selling that the Indian stone industry is plagued by. By selling at cheaper prices, we are only degrading the value of Indian stones. One might be able to supply reasonable quality at rock-bottom prices for a short period of time. But to do so consistently is not possible and eventually inferior quality material gets shipped. This undermines the faith that a customer has in the supplier, and ultimately in Indian stone industry. After all, at the end of the day, it is how well you can maintain a relationship of trust with your customers that matters in the long run.
Finally, manufacturers are selling rejected and commercial material to traders, who are in turn passing it on as good material. We must realize that by doing so we are damaging the market. The traders are able to sell the material to buyers abroad at a much cheaper price than others supplying first quality. Let us not encourage small and one time players bring disrespect to our community once again and instead work towards becoming world leaders.</td></tr>
